\tab Throughout the ages mankind have lived in fear and reverance of the Spirit world.  Ancestors have been looked at through time as guides and mentors to the families they belong to, on the other hand, many have shunned and feared spirits as demons and antagonists.  Spirits return to the world for various reasons, some to warn their loved ones, and others to bring them to the other side with them.\par
\par
\tab The Anima are the physical embodiment of purpose and devotion, their life let to deeds and tasks for the sake of loved ones or revenge.  Most Anima are dedicated to a certain emotion or tight knit group of emotions (i.e. hate, anger, revenge).  This purpose has allowed the anima a second chance at life, their purpose weaving their spirit into such a driven force as to give it physicality.\par
\par
The Becoming:  When a mortal dies, it usually passes on to another plane of existance.  However, when, certain things happen...certain things are left unfinished, the Anima are given a second chance.  The Anima must die in a way, leaving tasks unfinished.  The body and the spirit are seperated and the white tunnel appears.  However, for some reason, the Anima cannot pass through it and soon the tunnel closes, leaving the spirit trapped on this Earth.  An approved storyline is required to become an Anima.  Please note, the SL must be approved by the SL Dept. -before- your character dies.  This Breed is not to be used as an escape route if your character dies or if you suspect death, as per all Breed Changes requiring a SL you have 30 days in order to fulfill the requirements (Roleplaying and three (3) posts included on your Character Sheet) or the existing storyline becomes null and void.  Most changes to an Anima are a result of guidance from another existing one, taken in the form of them guiding you as you make the transition from the spirit world back to the land of the living.  In order to do this the existing Anima seeks you out and pulls you back, teaching you and guiding you.  This is done with 30 days of roleplaying after the characters death (Storyline makes the death occur) and the three required posts.  During this time your character is a ghost and cannot affect anything in the physical world, they are simply an observer.  When the time comes for you to cross over the existing Anima collects the items that will become your Anchors and gathers them, thenby focusing on the reality and physicality of those items he gives up a aprt of his purpose to bring you back.  The Anima must make a 2d6+Soul vs a TN of 14 in order to bring the new Anima into the world and solidify his spirit.  If this roll fails the subject is forced to spend another 30 days trapped in the afterlife, wandering and watching as he learns his focus.  Should the roll succeed, however, the new Anima gains physicality and manifests in purpose and destiny.  To this end, for this sacrifice the guiding Anima may select an Anchor to be removed without the loss of a Soul point (see RP requirements) and is one step further towards enlightenment.  (This creation post is required on the guides Character sheet as a link to the reolution of an Anchor).\par
\tab These Anchors are vital to the Anima\rquote s survival.  They are usually items that were significant in the Revenant's life.  It may be related to his or her task or simply something that was close to the his heart.  If the Touchstone is destroyed and his body is killed, the Anima loses his physical body and is doomed to wander, never to complete his task.  He is consigned for an eternity of endless, bodiless haunting.  If a Anima is more than 1 square mile from his Touchstone, he begins to lose Body at a rate of 1 point per hour.  If he returns to his Touchstone before he loses all of his Body, all Body points are returned instantly. If he does not return in time, then his body dies and he is trapped on this mortal coil forever.\par
\par
