Means of Recovery: An unenlightened Anima will regain 1 point of body every three days.  So they will recover from a knife wound in a few days, but a shotgun would take 12 days, or a little more than a week.  A member of this breed receiving professional care will recover at 2x the normal rate.  So that's about 1 point every day and a half.  A knife wound would require a day and a half, while a shotgun would require 6 days.  While injured, the character may role-play as normal, but must role-play their injuries (i.e. a person shot in the side would have it bandaged up and be very sore).  Also, remember the healing process isn't necessarily complete at the point they recover.  It simply means their bodies have returned to a normal using condition.  They may still have scars, stiffness or short, sharp pains.  How the injuries are role-played is up to the player.  Fire Causes 2 points of body damage for every round in contact with the Anima.  This damage heals at a rate of one point per week.  Basic or Major Medical can be used to to heal or accelerate the healing of any injuries.\par
\par
Lore Level 1:  You have watched many Hollywood movies and that is where you get most of your knowledge from.  You understand that ghosts exist but only mediums can talk to them.  You also think that many ghosts are malevolent and evil, liking to throw things around and smashing objects around houses.  You believe that ghosts may be trapped to a place, forced to haunt it by night.  They often carry chains and rattle and moan out.  When things go bad, who ya gonna call?  GHOSTBUSTERS!\par
\par
Laurels:  Laurels have been used throughout history to repel evil spirits and those of the dead.  These are traditionally placed near or above a door to repel the spirit from the home or to bar its entrance.  However the way this truly works is that by holding the Laurel out and wilding it against the Anima.  The character must brandish the Laurel and concentrate, focusing their faith through the object to ward them off.  This requires a roll of 2d6+Soul+Faith vs. The Anima's 2d6+Soul+Faith.  If the character beats the Anima's roll they are successfull and the Anima must flee the scene for the next 4 rounds / 2 minutes.  Nothing will dissuade the Anima from fleeing until the duration wears off.  This is a blind panic and the only actions that the Anima may make are those that will allow them to escape quicker.  Should there be no place to run, the Anima will collapse to the ground, cowering in fear.  If this attempt fails however, the Anima can ignore any further warding attempts by the same character for the next 4 rounds / 2 minutes.  The failed use of warding enrages the Anima and they will attack the character as their next action however they are able.  You may not ward a member of your own breed.\par
\par
Lore Level 2: You have done an incredible amount of reading on the subject of ghosts.  You understand that they are lost souls trying to get in touch with lost ones.  They may or may not be tied to one certain place and that they have the ability to materialize in the real world for some time.  Some are malovelent but some are good, it all depends on the Anima.  When an Anima uses a mental mastery with you as the target within line of sight from you, roll 2d6+Mind+2 vs. a TN: 20.  It matters not if you know the characters breed - your mind will still attempt to defend itself from attack, even though your physical self had no realization of the process.  If you succeed, you recognize the ability and its effect, giving you a one time +3 to the resistance roll (if any) for that mastery.  (masteries requiring the demon use Will, Mind or Soul rolls only; cannot be used while in direct combat).\par
\par
Lambs Blood:  Lambs Blood has been used as a symbol of protection and purity for aeons, this symbol of sacrifice wounds the Anima gravely.  It takes 10 minutes to empower enough blood for 1 attack.  This empowering must be role-played in the main room for the entire 10 minutes for it to work.  The character may hold the blood in a container of its choice, however glass baubles are most common. To attack with the blood, the attacker must use the Throwing Skill as per a normal attack.  Only 3 attacks worth of Lambs Blood may be empowered at one time.  If the character attempts to make more than 3 attacks worth, the first amount looses its ability, etc.  The empowered Blood may only be used by the individual that created it.  The roll to empower the blood is 2d6+Soul+Faith vs TN 22.  This roll must be witnessed and approved my either a room host, ST or GM.  If an attack is successful, the Anima suffers 1 point of damage that cannot be healed supernaturally.  The Anima must heal the damage as if it was caused by fire.  That would mean each point of damage would take 1 week.  Major Medical is the only medical skill that will help the Anima heal faster at the maximum rate of x2.\par
\par
Lore Level 3: You have studied ghosts most of your life, and perhaps you've even known a few.  You have finally discovered the truth about ghosts.  You know they are tied to certain objects or people and that these people and objects are the source of their ability to remain on this world.  You know that there are different types of Anima, (i.e.: poltergeists, caspers, spirits, etc.) that they all do different things.   When an Anima uses a mental mastery with you as the target within line of sight from you, roll 2d6+Mind+3 vs. a TN: 20.  It matters not if you know the characters breed - your mind will still attempt to defend itself from attack, even though your physical self had no realization of the process.  If you succeed, you recognize the ability and its effect, giving you a one time +5 to the resistance roll (if any) for that mastery.  (masteries requiring the demon use Will, Mind or Soul rolls only; cannot be used while in direct combat).\par
\par
Sight Recognition: There are two methods of identifying an Anima.  Not the identity of the person, but the identity of the breed.  Only through long hours of study (and the prerequisite Lore level 3) are these methods possible.  The first is by physically seeing the true form of the Anima, which happens to be Eidolon  If you wish to identify the Eidolon as a breed, roll 2d6 + Mind vs. TN 14.  If the roll is successful, you have gathered enough knowledge to understand that you are actually looking at an Anima, and not some illusion of the eyes.  The second method is by observing the Anima transform either to or from Eidolon.  If this is physically witnessed and there is a Room Host, ST or GM, the observer automatically recognizes what others may think of as 'swamp gas' or 'light flashes' as a Demon.\par
\par
Rubbing the Bones:  The Anima is a spirit with a mission when it arises from the grave.  Their body is only now a manifestation of their purpose.  No matter how much physical punishment the body absorbs the Man Body resists returning before it's task is complete. Yet there is a way to free an Anima from this overwheliming sense of being.  The first step is to create a bone talisman using bone from a human corpse.  This talisman may take any shape but it must have a bloodstone set into it, this talisman will be used to draw the purpose and Spirit of the Anima into itself and hold it for eternity.  The Man Body must first be brought to the negative equivalent of its body stat. Once this is achieved, the Attacker must take lead nails and nail each hand and foot of the Anima to the ground, this frees the spirit of purpose from the Man Body.  After this is done the character must concentrate and focus their faith through the talisman to draw to freed spirit into it, this requires a roll of 2d6+Soul+Faith vs. TN 26. If the character succeeds, the next round the the Anima's Restless Soul is lulled into the Talisman. However, if a Revenant is reduced to negative Body, but his Anchor is intact, he will be unconscious until the following evening.  The only way to kill a Revenant is to locate his Anchor, destroy it, and then kill the body.\par
